It is important to efficiently choose sample values for $\omega$ such that more samples are collected around points of interest, namely the resonance frequency. For the provided values of L and C, the predicted resonant frequency can be calculated according to Equation (\ref{resonance}) which is $\omega_0 = 67420rad/s \implies f = 10730Hz$.

Outside of this resonant frequency, beyond the 3dB cutoff, a constant rolloff is expected, and therefore not many measurements need to be taken in that region.

