\subsection{Resonant frequency analysis}
The first observation that is made is the noticeable peak at $f \approx 10700Hz$. That corresponds to our theoretical resonance frequency of $10730Hz$. It is also clear from the graph that the change in resistor value between $51\Omega$ and $100\Omega$ does not impact the resonant frequency as predicted by the resonance frequency equation in Equation (\ref{resonance}). The transfer function depicted shows the characteristics of a bandpass filter, where only a certain range of frequencies (between the 3dB cutoff frequencies) are not extremely attenuated.

\subsection{Q-factor and 3dB cutoff analysis}
The second observation is that the graph for $R=51\Omega$ is noticeably narrower than the graph for $R=100\Omega$. This is a confirmation of the prediction by Equation (\ref{qfactor}), as the Q-factor is lower when the series resistance in the LCR circuit is greater. 

The 3dB cutoff point is labelled by the grey horizontal line in the graph. As predicted by Equation (\ref{bandwidth}), the bandwidth with the $100\Omega$ resistor is wider as shown by the fact that more of the blue graph is above the line compared to the red graph.

Reading from Figure \ref{fig:transfer-focus}, we can estimate the following values for the bandwidth and Q-factors of the $100\Omega$ and $51\Omega$ resistors using Equation (\ref{bandwidth}) and Equation (\ref{qfactor}).

\begin{gather}
	\nonumber \Delta \omega_{51\Omega} = 11.6kHz - 9.64kHz = 1.96kHz \implies Q_{51\Omega} = 10.7kHz/1.96kHz = 5.45 \\
	\nonumber \Delta \omega_{100\Omega} = 12.98kHz - 8.44kHz = 4.54kHz \implies Q_{100\Omega} = 10.7kHz/4.54kHz = 2.37
\end{gather}

Reading from Figure (\ref{fig:transfer}), it is also visible that the slope of the graph well beyond the 3dB cutoff point is $\approx 25dB/decade$.

